text:
photos: #amberrose dresses as rauchy bride for her #2018 annual  #slutwalk

___

amber rose made for one very raunchy bride on saturday, as she led the way at her annual slutwalk in los angeles.

dressed in bridal-white underwwear - a flouncy basque, stockings and suspenders, she wore her blonde hair in ringlets under a veil.

___

the sexy take on a wedding dress was all part of the former stripper turned model and actress's annual slutwalk.

the 34-year-old star says the event has a role in raising awareness for the changes in attitude around the world.

__

she told harper's bazaar: 'well, we're not taking any s**t anymore. we're speaking up and we're not scared just because these men are in higher positions or they have more money or they intimidate us. 'we have a voice and we all realise now that's why slutwalk is so important -- to bring an awareness of actually what's happening in this world.

tis time.

text:
actual sex workers unequivocally supports the abolition of prisons and the police force. the decriminalisation of sex work in a world still at the mercy of violent police who fill our prisons with mostly black and brown people for crimes of poverty, or crimes they didnâ€™t commit at all, is not liberation. our fight for the decriminalisation of sex work is situated withinÂ  a broader struggle against capitalism, white supremacy and patriarchy. we stand in solidarity with all incarcerated and criminalised people. 
debbie kilroy is the founder and ceo of sisters inside inc, a qld based community organisation that advocates for the rights of women prisoners. kilroy, having first hand experience of incarceration, is a dedicated prison abolitionist and has made an overwhelmingly positive contribution to the community. sisters inside state on their website that â€œprisons are an irrational social response. in our society, prisons only function to punish and socially ostracise law breakersâ€ it comes as quite a surprise then to find out that kilroy is a rusted on proponent of the swedish model, a form of sex work criminalisation. kilroy argues: â€œfree market capitalism is not the answer and will not stop violence against women and girls. legalized prostitution is government-sanctioned abuse of women and girls, and violates their rights to safety and equality... we need to not decriminalize. we need to hold men, pimps, johns accountable for their violation of women." the myriad contradictions and falsehoods in this statement alone are too numerous to cover in this short rant. but i will say this, the swedish model is not compatible with prison abolition. the swedish model is simply a manifestation of the white saviour complex that disproportionately fucks over poc, migrants, aboriginal and torres strait isislander, trans and otherwise marginalised folk. it sees increased policing of these communities who are already over policed. the swedish model strengthens rather than challenges the carceral state. the mental hoops one must jump through to simultaneously support further criminalising a community and prison abolition is mind blowing. [cont in comments]

text:
for the members of this community who have experienced sexual assault or trauma of of some kind, i stand in solidarity with you. for the women (and men) who have carried their pain with them, i create a safe place for you and reassure you that you are seen and safe with me here. *please take a moment to listen to these videos.* i am not a therapist. i am not trained to offer you tools to work through your healing. but i am your sister. and i will tell you, that you are not alone. you are valuable. your trauma does not have to define how you live your life. if you are someone who has tried to speak up in the past but has not been heard... i wish i could do more for you. i can't. just know that i am here. i see you. and i will listen.

i experienced sexual trauma within the context of, what i thought was, a loving relationship from the summer before i turned 18 till the time i was 20. it also took me my entire adult life to be able to see that trauma and understand, first,  that it was wrong and, second, that it was not something i deserved.

i hope in my sharing that (i am not comfortable sharing more - please respect that, and it's not because i don't care about you it's that i don't know that i am ready or ever will) you have some space to feel comforted in community.

long story made short. i love you guys.
ğŸ’š

text:
#ransomriggs #amapofdays #staypeculiar #messyhairdontcare 
i met one of my favorite writers today. i was really, really hoping that my hips would cooperate with me. luckily, they did. most of the week has lead to me feeling like my hips and thighs are in fire. they've been subluxating non-stop most of the week, but finally calmed down sometime last night.

i asked him two questions. one, about how the #metoo movement may have inspired how he writes female characters. he said it hasn't intentionally, but he's inspired and awed by the brave women who've comd forward. also, sometimes you don't know what inspires something until years later.

he gave great advice about how to write while disabled. says people want to hear what you have to say, so don't give up. just find what works for you. â¤

text:
another tl;dr but this time with trigger warnings for sexual assault. the most iâ€™ve ever put on social media but as many heroes of mine have said recently, the time to stay quiet is gone. 
so the video iâ€™m sharing is very powerful and will be seriously triggering if you are a survivor of sexual assault but i would hope you find catharsis in it as i have. for me, as a fellow survivor, a piece of art has never given me the healing and solace in the same way as this song and video: mr weinstein will see you now.  https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=juubxnkgns8&feature=youtu.be

it goes to the depths of what continues to haunt me and i know, now, many others. the fear of my own part in the experience, the terror of the ambiguity, the endless self analysis and questioning my self. internalised victim shaming and blaming, the same tired tropes playing out despite my ardent feminism. struggling to even own it as assault until two wonderful people could reflect otherwise.

the reality being that someone i trusted greatly, totally violated my boundaries. the reality being that had the cultural discourse been what it is now, the signs were all there that he was far from trustworthy. 
the reality now is that the discourse has changed and we are experiencing a tsunami of stories and experiences. the collective pain is ferocious and unending - but it is the beginning of a sea change. even as we retain social norms that allow aggressive sexual predators into the highest legal and political offices. we will not be silenced and we must let this tide turn from the white, supremacist heteronormative patriarchy to intersectionality and inclusivity.

if you donâ€™t consider yourself part of this movement as a survivor or even in solidarity, (if you donâ€™t feel the latter, iâ€™m open to discussion), but consider yourself a purveyor of extraordinary art that captures the zeitgeist, then this video is still for you. thank you @amandapalmer and @jasziepower and the team in and behind the video ğŸ’ªğŸ»ğŸ’ªğŸ»ğŸ’ªğŸ» #metoo #whyididntreportit #timesup #enoughisenough #istandwithher #mrweinsteinwillseeyounow #amandapalmer #jasminepower

text:
just finished mom and son yoga in the park with the calling of the crows and the ants wiggling their way onto our mats. i wanted to share my practice with him this morning. it isnâ€™t the same as practicing by myself, but part of the healing aspect of yoga is community.
.
we are social creatures and need each other. we need to know we are not alone in our struggles.
.
we also need that connection with nature. we are part of this ecosystem not above it..
.
i feel that this is a time when we feel divided. yoga means union. it is time to come together not ripping each other apart. .

what does #believesurvivors #listentosurvivors mean? it means showing through action that our stories, our pain, our trauma matter.
.
walking the talk of justice means sacrificing personal comfort to do the right thing. survivors have entire intense pain and are changed for the rest of their lives because of the awful actions of one person.
.
it's honestly not asking a lot for non-survivors to suck it up and make a sliver of the sacrifice that survivors do on a daily basis.
.
shame on the pro-kavanaugh people who are willing to sacrifice the well-being and safety of millions of americans for their personal gain. shame on colleges who insist on giving rapists degrees. shame on companies that hire and promote abusers. shame on churches that shuttle sexual abusers through their systems.
.
it takes a village to protect a rapist. it's the easy thing to do.
.
want to fight rape culture? want to prove that you actually believe survivors? stop. being. lazy. and. hold. abusers. accountable.
.
they're not victims. they are individuals who need to face consequences for their actions.
.
phew ok! i wasn't expecting for this to turn into a rant. but here we are!
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
in an attempt to help me
reach my sleep
there is a list i speak
rather than cut and weep
.
(in truth, 
it's not the longest list, 
but if you pay attention,
you already have the gist.)
.
i name my enemies
one by one, 
as a promise to myself
not to forget what they've done.
.
and should these motherfuckers win
then i say let the revolution begin. 
perhaps then these pigs will pay their debt.
and like arya, i promise:
a girl does not forget.
.
black.rabbit.poetry, october 6, 2018
.

text:
a timely moment and one of joy during this kavanaugh mess. it was an honor to meet these women who work tirelessly for all of us. i'm so motivated right now!!! i'm excited and scared at the same time to see my project @afacetoit off the ground. so much more work to be done but i'm #feelingthefearanddoingitanyway
â€¢ â€¢ â€¢
last saturday at this exact time, two phenomenal women, @chasinggarza & @osopepatrisse founders of the #blm movement, courageously painted their hands in #solidarity w/survivors of domestic violence & sexual assault at the #rpnc2018 conference. thank you!

it is an honor to co-create and curate this living interactive art-ivist piece. this piece is a part of my #afacetoit project, which i presented a preview at the @raceandpedagogyinstitute conference. i'm humbled by the survivors who courageously left their mark. some of the participants had never told anyone, yet stepped up and painted their hands. we hugged, we cried, we smiled and we celebrated the freedom this interaction gave us. unfortunately, i had a man tell me that we need "more than paint" to raise awareness. he and people like him, need to know that these forms of expression are also very important!  they help us in the healing process, without the fear of shame or ridicule from others. i was thanked, but i did this for all of us. our stories are important. (emotions are welling up as i type this) thank you from the bottom of my heart survivors!

thank you #rpnc2018 for helping to make this possible

.

text: i was struggling whether to post regarding the current state of affairs. after reflecting i decided i need to, not because it is easy but because it is right. women's rights being attacked is a danger to all of us. women make up half of the population. #metoo is being criticized. fear and hate continue to try to divide us and make men the victims. men are victims too.1 in 6 men also get sexually assaulted. i want to be clear feminism is about #equality !we are your mothers, sisters, daughters, wives, coworkers, and friends and we fiercly love the men who love and support us. #unitedwearestronger i'm so thankful for these men, especially this guy here. he has and continues to teach me how to come back to love. we all have cracks in our hearts.  #supporteachother thank you to the brave women marching, and speaking out! let's also show some appreciation to the men who love us and teach us to continue to love with our broken hearts. #believesurvivors #himtoo #strongertogether

text:
si's shirt says "tough dude." he will grow up being taught that to be tough is to be vulnerable, honest, patient and loving. 
being tough is not outward anger hiding pain, shame and confusion underneath. being tough is sharing your feelings, admitting mistakes, practicing humility and knowing you don't know all.

men, we get to redefine "tough" and teach true power for future generations. it starts today.

and if you want support in that, come check out a group a number of twin cities men have started called detoxifying masculinity. we meet the second tuesday of every month (730-9pm) at public functionary (1400 12th ave ne mpls). there is more info on @intertwinene
meetup page or on facebook as detoxifying masculinity - twin cities.

#men #man #toxicmasculinity #masculinity #father #parenting #boys #istandwithsurvivors #breakthesilence #metoo #detoxifyingmasculinity

text:
rosary solimanto is performing a free 30 minute artwork at dixon place, revealing her true story, expose: disability, trauma and shame. she divulges her story of multiple sclerosis becoming the best thing that ever happened to her. it begins 20 years ago when she became blind, couldnâ€™t walk, and diagnosed with multiple sclerosis. the performance begins in complete darkness, â€œif we could only hear people and not see them â€¦â€ her oppression and stigmas of living with a disability unravels into her new identity becoming her artistic career. "the government, medical community and society describes me as weak and a drain on the system. yet they have forced this life of poverty, seclusion, and shame upon me. i will not live in shame because of my body and mind, and what they have done to me." solimanto explores agency and intersectional identity from the inside of her body where human identity interconnects us all as pre-existing conditions. years ago when solimantoâ€™s health was on a rapid decline due to western medicines treatments she was forced to take agency of her body, educate herself in all aspects of medicine and science in order to regain her health and mobility. she found her strength and power by taking control back of the treatments done to her body. the affects of health conditions on one's life can create a slippery slope from poverty, rape, depression, trauma and exclusion. all of solimantoâ€™s current health conditions are invisible afflictions, as are 80% of people with disabilities live with invisible impairments. and 1 out of 2 people have a health condition. invisible health conditions are the most stigmatized, as they are not seen, but only experienced. 
the goal of solimantoâ€™s work is to advocate disability pride and awareness to women with health conditions in order to imbue their condition with fascination and empowerment. 
free tickets in bio and link here: https://web.ovationtix.com/trs/pe/10335191 .

huge congratulations to 2018 #nobelpeaceprize laureate, nadia murad, who has been a brave and powerful voice for survivors of human trafficking and victims of sexual violence. in 2014, at the age of 19, murad was kidnapped in iraq, held hostage, and constantly subjected to sexual violence. after escaping 3 months of captivity, she started seeking justice for victims everywhere, telling her story to the world time and again, even though that meant reliving horrific memories of abuse and suffering. thank you nadia, for your courage to speak up and seek justice, not just for yourself, but for all survivors of sexual violence.

text:
i had an emotional reaction to this affirmation yesterday.

for survivors of trauma, the sentence, "i am safe" can seem foreign or unfamiliar. after years of unpredictability, abuse and fear, "safety" was not my norm.

as i was affirming it to myself yesterday, i couldn't help but cry because it felt odd, and i realize i don't believe this yet. i'm not 100% ready to settle and believe i'm safe. i'm close. but not yet.

so i will continue to affirm this to myself regularly, because soon i will believe it. and rest in the peace of it.

still a queen ğŸ‘‘âœŠ.

text:
hey guys.... you remember your first time in jail? your first fight? first war? first (insert anything that brings possible physical harm and/or death)? that feeling of paranoia that so many different physical harms could happen to you at any given moment. and/or the feeling of being on guard, all...the...time.

this is what i imagine a lot of women go through. all the time, throughout a womanâ€™s life, from beginning to end. 
some find strength, others find a way out (living or dying), but most sweep it under the rug thinking, or convinced, this is the way it is and it wonâ€™t change. and they may be right. 
if you have never been raped, impregnated, bleed out of your peehole for a week every month for most of your life or anything in between, donâ€™t try to relate. donâ€™t say you understand. 
if you have, youâ€™re not alone. but you still donâ€™t know the full length of what itâ€™s like to live in that all youâ€™re life. or the mindset it brings from years of being in that despair (some guys may. and iâ€™m sorry if thatâ€™s the case. this post is not towards you at all). just like jail, sooner or later, the only thing you know is your cell. itâ€™s your safe haven. now try to picture that if you can...your cell, being your safe place. but anytime you leave that place, good luck.

this is not a kavanaugh rant. iâ€™m just kind of tired of hearing some dudes talk like they know everything. when itâ€™s impossible unless you are, in fact, a woman. youâ€™re guessing at best! youâ€™re coming to a conclusion that makes the most sense to you, a man. now how does that even make sense?

trust me, itâ€™s better to ask questions. care enough to at least have a convo. but never try to say you know whatâ€™s happening in a womanâ€™s mind or body. 
by all means unfriend me if this pisses you off. but if you at least have an open mind, letâ€™s have a civil discussion. 
#metoo

text:
it is almost impossible to come forward.  it is the hardest thing i ever had to do.  i knew the risk, i knew it would probably come with great loss for me, and others involved.  i knew that.  i thought about it for years, everyday.  i had nightmares about it and about coming forward.  in the end it was the right choice.  i lost family. i received hateful messages from family. i went to the police, i had friends and family go to the police for me too.  i had the police call me and tell me they couldn't go further, that the crown decided because family was siding with him there was nothing they could do.  i have had people look at me like a broken victim, i have had people say horrible mean things because they didn't understand.  i have had sleepless night, hard days, impossible moments.  i have had to live everyday with the pain someone else caused me. 
but i can look back at all that and know i did the right thing.  i did what was best for me and my family, but what is more i did what was right for every other person who has lived a similar situation.  i was a voice for people who didn't feel like they had a voice.

so if i made a difference in my tiny circle of influence, imagine the difference dr.ford has made!  she has been a voice, a loud voice, even though it has caused her great pain, even though she has been mocked by the president of the united states. she has stood up for herself and for millions of others who couldn't be as loud as her. she is a hero! she is who i want to be when i grow up.  you remember when you were a kid and people would say to you "you can be anything when you grow up, even the president!" i don't know about you but i would much rather my children grow up to people who believe in themselves, who stand up when something is wrong, who go against the mean giants.  i want my children to be strong and amazing like dr.ford, like their mother.

text:
over the past few weeks, clients have brought their personal struggles and pain around their experiences with sexual assaults to light in many sessions. the shame and guilt triggered by a daily reminder that our society does not favor or believe the victim, and in fact rewards the perpetrator in some cases. i have struggled to hold their stories and their pain without my own rage clouding my vision. it is my personal work to provide what they need in those moments, even if that is only an ear and a soft word, no matter how hard that is.
âœ¨
i truly believe what we have been witnessing over the past 2 years is the deepest shadows of our society being brought to light. being made conscious so we can look it in the eyes and face it in a way we never have. i am trusting daily in this process of growth and integration and trying not to get overwhelmed by a feeling of sadness and what sometimes feels like an unimaginable rage, but rather sitting with it, getting familiar with it, and trying to direct it into action. #neverthelessshepersisted

text:
*
.
.
the drooling race
.
.
how long before a movement
turns into a race?
how long before good sense
becomes disgrace?
how long before greed
outruns our race?

how long before smiles
turn back to growl and boo?
how long before 'she did' or 'he did'
shames the tradition of 'i do'?
how long before the wolves
begin baying #metoo?
.
.

arvind passey

.

text:
a year after the birth of the #metoo movement, much has changed and nothing has changed. victim blaming is on the rise again having seen and experienced it myself from fans, friends, and other people @adamcroasdell has enlisted towards myself and his other victims shows me how malicious and unsafe this world can be for victims. actions from them and him is #whyididntreport on top of living in fear of him and their threats. my silence gave him a thirst for more and younger victims. i realize and know wholeheartedly he will never stop. his fans, friends, and family are his accomplices by victim shaming and he shows no remorse for the pain he causes he feels proud. in other words, if youâ€™re waiting for them to make an apology, forget it. these men might regret getting caught. but expressing true remorse about the damage they caused isnâ€™t forthcoming. what most of them havenâ€™t lost is the conviction that since they are either celebrities, men in power from business to political power they have the right to treat women as they please, not the women we are to bow down live with the nightmare. i decided to no longer suffer in silence but men like adam croasdell we stand up to or say no to feel they are the real victims and, as such, do not need to change their behavior and continue the cycle of abuse making it worse and enlist others to abuse their victims. adam croasdell is one of the many men during the #metoo era included in some of the most shameful chapters in the history of the united states because it shows his complicity and what men of his ilk will do to hurt women and hide it. 
#nomore #speakupagainstadamcroasdell

text:
you can recognize survivors of abuse by their courage. when silence is so very inviting, they step forward and share their truth so others know they aren't alone. #metoo i was a victim of adam croasdell and will not be silenced, threatened or shamed as a survivor for his actions anymore by him or whomever he has help him whether fans or friends he enlists. in november our joint interviews will be airing stateside. we will be sharing our experiences as a survivor of his abuse, pictures to videos in conjunction and the various methods he used to try and silence us. iâ€™m one of five women who have spoken up and been interviewed if adam croasdell has physically or mentally abused you or harassed your under multiple instagrams whether alone or with fans or his friends please come forward with hashtag #adamcroasdellabusedmetoo we would like to have you interviewed and speak out  against him to stop him from silencing another woman if youâ€™re scared and have any chat logs, texts, videos, audios or pictures we will take those to if you prefer to not be named but still want to help. your safety is more important and adam has a history of bullying and harassing women whether by internet or outside of it it does not matter if it happened on or offline. there are also six photographers who are going to interview and sue him for violating their copyrights, harassment and vandalism of their work which he did under multiple instagrams if heâ€™s done that to you to please let us know we will give you the information for that process use #adamcroasdellvandalized thank you for your help and supporting and stopping adam from vandalizing photographers work and other women from being hurt by this animal. if we stay silent we empower abusers creating more women to be victims. we need to support survivors instead of shaming or blaming them because a celebrity or person in power commits these atrocities.

text:
"i think that it's a very scary time for young men in america when you can be guilty of something that you may not be guilty of," trump said tuesday afternoon outside the white house.
.
back in 1989, trump had no fear of shatteringÂ lives. in fact, heÂ led a lynch mob, taking out full page advertisements in every new york paper demanding that the death penalty be applied in the central park jogger case.
.
the nypd had arrested five black or brown children between 14 and 16 to demonstrate speedy progress after a horrific assault that led a young woman fighting for her life. npyd detectives forced confessions, in theÂ absence of lawyers or parents, from 4 of the 5 children.
reflecting on that moment decades later, one of the young boys, yusuf salaam said:
.
â€œhe was the fire starter,â€ salaam said of trump, in his first extended interview since trump announced his run for the white house. â€œcommon citizens were being manipulated and swayed into believing that we were guilty.â€ â€”Â www.theguardian.com/...
.
#yusefsalaam, #kevinrichardson, #koreywise, #antronmccray, and #raymondsantana, the five children who wereÂ falsely accused of rape and assault by #donaldtrump were eventually exonerated in 2002.Â no physical evidence had ever tied them to the victim or the scene, but theyâ€™d been convicted nonetheless, on the basis of coerced confessions extracted by an out of control and inept nypd. over a decadeÂ after their convictions, dna evidence implicated a known sex offender. nypd detectives had botched the case and let a dangerous rapist roam free for years. the city paid tens of millions in a settlement to the central park five, who spent most of their youth behind bars on false charges.
.
the five children spent between 5 and 15 years in jail. their lives were shattered by donald trump, his ego, and his #racism. he was the fire starter.

text:
last saturday at this exact time, two phenomenal women, @chasinggarza & @osopepatrisse, courageously painted their hands in #solidarity w/survivors of domestic violence & sexual assault at the #rpnc2018 conference. thank you!

it is an honor to co-create and curate this living interactive art-ivist piece. this piece is a part of my #afacetoit project, which i presented a preview at the @raceandpedagogyinstitute conference. i'm humbled by the survivors who courageously left their mark. some of the participants had never told anyone, yet stepped up and painted their hands. we hugged, we cried, we smiled and we celebrated the freedom this interaction gave us. unfortunately, i had a man tell me that we need "more than paint" to raise awareness. he and people like him, need to know that these forms of expression are also very important! they help us in the healing process, without the fear of shame or ridicule from others. i was thanked, but i did this for all of us. our stories are important. (emotions are welling up as i type this) thank you from the bottom of my heart survivors!

thank you #rpnc2018 for helping to make this possible

link: https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/06/opinion/me-too-weinstein-one-year.html?smtyp=cur&smid=tw-nytopinion 
@regran_ed from @amberrosetamblyn -  i wrote a short piece for the new york times. i still have hope. in spite of it all. â€œamericaâ€™s never-ending procession of survivors of sexual assault and harassment being disbelieved has me thinking about something i wrote a few weeks before the #metoo movement broke wide open â€” an essay that, for me, felt less like an opinion and more like a desperate declaration. i told a story about a famous older actor who hit on me when i was 16 years old; he called me a liar online, and his followers jumped to brand me as unbelievable. i proclaimed that i was done with not being believed, a sentiment that resonated for any woman who has ever told her story or been intimidated into not telling her story.

today, i find myself wondering what has changed. i watched a measured and reserved christine blasey ford face a firing squad of male republican senators as the man she accused of sexually assaulting her wielded a type of raw, emotional freedom that women have rarely been allowed to display. watching her story essentially be discarded by the senate felt like the reflection of the universal womanâ€™s experience, an all too familiar reality.
but the truth is, absolutely everything has changed for us, however incremental those changes may be. women and survivors are no longer asking for permission to speak. we are forcing the world to listen â€” and in doing so, to change.â€ - #regrann

text:
[cw: sexual violence]
.
.
.

this morning i'm cheating a bit on my own #tarottuneschallenge. i designed the challenge to highlight one song for each of the major arcana cards, but right now i'm feeling pulled toward choosing more than one. the hierophant card calls us to question what we've been taught. we all absorb messages from people in positions of power through the course of our lives. with this card, we are asked to discern between which teachings align with our sense of self and which are harmful bullshit that does not support the ways in which we want to show up in the world. we choose for ourselves, rather than falling into blind acceptance or dogma.

in the wake of the #metoo movement and supreme court hearings, i've found myself angry that none of the adults in my life ever spoke to my teenage self or my peers about #consent in any meaningful way. in short, i never reported my sexual assault because i thought i'd get in trouble for it. looking back, i was clearly hurting and not one adult ever asked me what was wrong. i began learning about consent and sexual agency from listening to @toriamos music and interviews when i was in high school. songs like â€œsilent all these years,â€ â€œprecious things,â€ â€œicicle,â€ and â€œblack-dove (january)â€ honestly taught me more and helped me move forward more than anything the adults who were supposed to be looking out for me ever did.

yesterday i felt angry and powerless. this morning i'm still angry, but i'm not powerless. i set up a small monthly donation to @rainn, which uses 93 cents of every dollar donated to help survivors and prevent sexual violence. rainn received more calls and chat messages from survivors after dr. ford's testimony than they have on any day since they were established in 1994.

keep shedding what makes you feel small, keep thinking critically about what messages you've internalized from those in positions of power, keep showing up for what matters to you, keep rejecting anything that does not recognize your full humanity or the humanity of others, keep holding on to each other and to yourself with compassion.

text: #saturdaythoughts waking up this morning to the news that kavanaugh was most likely going to be confirmed to the supreme court of the united states of america today...was not something i was actually prepared for... i guess i didn't expect our shitty government to rush so quickly to try to put this pos into a place of power where he can do a lot of damage in ways that the people of this country either aren't thinking about or don't "believe" are actually things that matter. and this is mostly just incoherent rambling, because while i knew this country sucks, it still is quite the blow every time shit happens to keep reminding us just how much of a clusterfuck we have become... how in the fuck are we going backwards, where we are fearful of having rights that were already fought for and finally "given", even though all people have the same exact rights, being once again "banned" by our governing system, which is absolute bullshit?! i can't even with the rage i am feeling right now... i just want dr. christine blasey ford to know that she stood for what was right, even though it was hard af. and i for one will never forget her bravery. and unless anyone has been in the position she was in, to have to go before the entire fucking country, reveal your most vulnerable and darkest painful moment, facing the person who assaulted and attacked you, and doing so in front of the most powerful people in our nation, knowing they were going to mock and ridicule her in this way, but she still did it anyway, to at least do her part to try to prevent a man who actually attacked girls from fucking with the rights of women who might be attacked by "boys just like him"... she is a goddamn hero. i see you, dr. ford. and i thank you for doing your best to protect us all, women and men, from kavanaugh. i am so deeply sorry for the disgusting way the people of this nation, both those "in positions of power" and "regular people", have treated you with such disrespect. this has truly revealed the lack of empathy and the deep disregard that has been bred into our society. you are a true warrior and fighter, and dr. ford, i appreciate you, because #metoo ğŸ’” #believesurvivors #believewomen

text:
i wrote a short piece for the new york times. i still have hope. in spite of it all. :::
â€œamericaâ€™s never-ending procession of survivors of sexual assault and harassment being disbelieved has me thinking about something i wrote a few weeks before the #metoo movement broke wide open â€” an essay that, for me, felt less like an opinion and more like a desperate declaration. i told a story about a famous older actor who hit on me when i was 16 years old; he called me a liar online, and his followers jumped to brand me as unbelievable. i proclaimed that i was done with not being believed, a sentiment that resonated for any woman who has ever told her story or been intimidated into not telling her story.

today, i find myself wondering what has changed. i watched a measured and reserved christine blasey ford face a firing squad of male republican senators as the man she accused of sexually assaulting her wielded a type of raw, emotional freedom that women have rarely been allowed to display. watching her story essentially be discarded by the senate felt like the reflection of the universal womanâ€™s experience, an all too familiar reality.
but the truth is, absolutely everything has changed for us, however incremental those changes may be. women and survivors are no longer asking for permission to speak. we are forcing the world to listen â€” and in doing so, to change.â€

text:
police likely to invite cristiano ronaldo for questioning over las vegas rape claim, says american detective.

juventus striker, cristiano ronaldo is likely to be invited by the police for questioning over his rape allegations as detectives prepare to bring new methods to their investigation.

the las vegas police have refused to reveal more details since after they had re-opened the case, but a us detective who ha handled 1,200 sexual assault cases said he had no doubt the force would want to question ronaldo over 34-year-old kathryn mayorgaâ€™s claims, at a time when the #metoo movement has triggered the re-opening of hundreds of historic allegations.

according to the report by daily mail, ronaldoâ€™s alleged victim may be asked to undertake a new form of psychological assessment, designed to trigger memories of the night in june 2009 when she was with the footballer.

the american detectives are reportedly finding increasing success in focusing on what they call â€˜neurobiological traumaâ€™, which allows those who allege sexual assault to recall details years later.

ronaldo has repeatedly denied the rape allegations against him, but the court documents, first published by der spiegel, show that ronaldoâ€™s lawyers paid ms. mayorga, a teacher, $375,000 (Â£228,000) to maintain her silence on what happened in a bathroom at the palms hotel and casino in las vegas.

it is understood that ronaldo maintains any sexual encounter between him and mayorga was entirely consensual.

text:
i was sexually assaulted when i was 15, by someone close to me, someone i trusted, a member of extended family. i have only told people about it in the last few years. i didnâ€™t really want to believe it myself. i felt, i still feel, a lot of shame when i think about it so it has been my deep, dark secret for a long time .
.
.
there are lots of things about it that i canâ€™t remember
.
.
.
the things i can remember are the feeling of his hands on top of my tights. being rigid with fear. pretending to be asleep
.
.
.
no one else was there. no corroborating witnesses
.
.
.
i know for a fact he did it to other people but if there were an investigation and they only used his testimony and didnâ€™t speak to the other women, the outcome would certainly be not guilty
.
.
.
most of the women i know have been sexually assaulted or harassed. we must change things. starting with telling the truth. no more secrets
.
.
.

she's discharging it under the name kittin, which is the first name she picked at the beginning of her vocation more than two decades back. (truth be told promoters frequently included the prefix "miss" without her assent, and the name in the end stuck.) "by liberating herself from the constraints of formal structure," the label continues, "she opens the door to a new set of aesthetics, exploring her influences without restraint." here the album tracklist

"two days ago, amber heardâ€™s lawyers professed their 'outrage' to the media that johnny depp had finally spoken in self-defense," depp lawyer adam waldman of the endeavor group wrote in a statement to the hollywood reporter on friday. "our evidence will include photographs, sworn testimony and admissions, and eyewitness accounts," waldman wrote. "ms. heard, who has a prior arrest for domestic abuse, and her lawyers have responded to these remarkable disclosures with two days of profound silence, excepting social media posts of ms. heard wrapped in an american flag asserting: 'we survivorsâ€¦'" waldman concludes, "ms. heardâ€™s lawyer publicly claimed ms. heard has unconsulted witnesses, but none have materialized. we would like to hear, and believe the public should hear, what, if anything, such 'witnesses' have to say, so that those statements may be held to account against our imminent court filings." johnny depp is innocent!!! #amberheard #metoo #johnnydepp #wearewithyoujohnnydepp #justiceforjohnnydepp #youcantkeepagoodmandown #istandwithjohnnydepp #proudofjohnnydepp

text:
my heart hurts.. to read the heartbreak,
of our #metoo stories,
so many i know,
so many we don't know.

why,
because we were exploring the free world,
where the rules are just off centre,
a special world twas to me,
no more, i dont see.

girls, women, fellow survivors,
i stand right by thee, unstintingly,
unafraid. 
girls,
i bring generations of fiery women,
even better,
i bring a tribe of honourable men,
who will not have it.

fight fire with fire.

boys. men.
hear me !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! step up, wontcha !! tis a fellow man, doing this.

stop him,wontcha. 
#colour #purple #womens #suffragette

text:
me too 
i am posting this tonight because i have been living under a cave, literally, and haven't been online on twitter or facebook to know that me too has finally begun its juggernaut in india over the course of this week. 
i am posting this because i love playing words with friends (it's a game like scrabble) and it's played with strangers and friends. once you play a couple of moves, the chat feature opens up on the game. i have made a couple good friends on it and gained some valuable insights and learned amazing new words.

but literally, every time over the last one month that i have tried to play with men (yes, men specifically) almost all chats have gone the same direction. how old are u? are you married? you're gorgeous do you know that?

and i always, always try and brush it off because you really do that. or maybe i am just one of many women who does that. but this, this was so troubling and hurtful. on so many levels.

1. i just wanted to play the goddamn game.
2. i don't care for conversation (which another player pointed out as 'i am trying to make friends here')
3. is it so fucking wrong to just want to play the goddamn game and not have to navigate yet another conversational landmine?

to anyone who asks me why i cropped the man's name out, i did so because i wanted to tell all the women brave enough to call out on their abusers, their tormentors, it's happened to me too. in multiple ways, with men who have been closer to me than some random guy texting me on an app halfway across the world. that is all.

to whoever wants to have an honest discussion about sexual harassment and it's ramifications, i'd be happy to engage. but please. be kind. be empathetic.

thanks.

writer gal

text:
it is wonderful that the media is joining in the #metoo campaign. now i have a request to make of every person here. take a closer look at where you work. does your company (startup or mnc) have a clearly laid out policy against harassment? some institutions call it posh (prevention of sexual harassment). it is required by law for every company to have a internal complaints commitee for the same in every organisation ( to the best of my knowledge).. and even if it's not mandatory, it is definitely a great practice to make this a part of your office culture. making this a part of your induction sends out the right message of "zero tolerance". the details of the icc (internal complaint committee) should be displayed prominently in company premises and sessions should be conducted to create awareness on what is acceptable behaviour and what is not. people should know the channels to raise complaints.

a word of caution to the startup community... since we are always in a fight for survival, we tend to put these actions on the back burner. don't let that happen here. it is not just a question of this being an ugly affair but also one that is just wrong as far as your human values go.

to the girls out there who have been victims of such incidents at work.. if you keep quiet today, you are responsible for what happens to another girl tomorrow.

#posh #preventionofsexualharrasement
#womenhelpingwomen #womensafety #womenempowerment #startup #startupculture

text:
my classes are really affecting me in a way i hadnâ€™t expected. some psyc classes i have pushed back to really make the timing work better with what happens in my personal life. 
but i have to admit i never felt such a turmoil inside while reading a textbook. 
forensic psychology is making me relive my past, change my views on some events and reconsider some things i had taken for granted. 
the positive i do see in all of this is that i was loved. some children go through pain and misery and never feel that unconditional love your parents should give you. 
i am grateful that i did feel loved. i have had many people do their best to compensate for what was taken from me. 
and still today i am so thankful to have the strongest women around to make me feel loved.
ps the picture is of my grandmother and i. she is my mother figure, she might not have given birth to me but she has been there from day one and has made sure i never forgot that i had â€œmy roomâ€ to come back too.
#nothingisevereasy #grateful #gratitude #stolenchildhood #metoo #womenempowerment #childabuse #amotherisnotalwaysamom #grandmafeels

text:
#metoo 
it isnâ€™t just a hashtag, itâ€™s a painful memory, a constant struggle, nightmares, insecurities, shame, hurt and so much more. but itâ€™s #mytruth and iâ€™m not ashamed of it. 
my childhood as well as self worth and love was stolen from me and most of my young adult life, but today and everyday after today iâ€™m choosing to #lovemyself and my story. 
i have struggled with finding comfortability in my sexuality and my relationship with sex has been more than complicated. i have allowed people to use me and place love in things that are in no shape or form of love. being taken advantage of at the most vulnerable time of your life leaves you with years of healing to do. but i have risen above being a victim. i am a survivor and i have overcome many things in life. iâ€™ve learned to open my heart. iâ€™m receiving and giving love after years of thinking i wasnâ€™t worthy of love! i am strong. we are strong! 
for decades woman have been brutalized, brainwashed into hating themselves and told they were â€œlyingâ€ or â€œwanted itâ€. but this #metoomovement has shown me that iâ€™m not alone. all of you feel my pain and i feel all of yours. our stories might be different but we all hurt the same. i see myself in all of you and i see all of you in me. itâ€™s time to get rid of the shame and hate and love ourselves. i send all my love to everyone and hope i can send you the light you need. 
youâ€™re beautiful
youâ€™re worthy
youâ€™re strong 
your truth deserves to be spoken! 
#believesurvivors

text:
ready to ship
.
letâ€™s box up the misogyny
and ship it to the sewage treatment plant
where it always did belong
.
as weâ€™ve been ordered by mail
by menu
by lineup
by cash
for all too long
.
having to pretend to enjoy
the erased face
the prison of being pretty
or touched 
by the ill-willed 
and brought to sorrow
in a bed
.
taught to be guarded
when simply heading to a show
or requesting a tow
or buying a garden hose
.
your gnawing can only continue
for so long
for earth
she can throw lava
at bad little boys
with great ease
.
she is the one woman
youâ€™ve no hope of taming
of beating
of raping
of repressing
for she is the all-dominant woman
consuming you
.
and upon her
your bigoted machismo 
is but an endearing and pathetic 
spot of nothing special
.
naugh gnaw
gnaw naugh
we can see you
.

text_retweet:
#repost @ekaterinaandersen with @get_repost
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
a year after #metoo. nothing has changed. weâ€™ve achieved nothing on the front of fighting sexism but having slightly more diverse models selling us products that we, as women, supposedly need. 
because when a man sits by the dinner table and he sees his wife, his sister, his daughter and his granddaughter being upset by something, he doesnâ€™t register this as his own problem. he registers this as a women problem, he doesnâ€™t feel the urge to participate.

and when the statistic that every third woman in the world gets assaulted comes up, he says â€œwell, i am not the part of the problem. i would never assault a woman.â€ and walks away. what would our society be if thatâ€™s how we reacted to all other crimes? if we would dismiss any evidence of a problem, just because we didnâ€™t personally cause it?

then there are the men who do get upset by it. and participate to the extent of also being upset by the dinner table, where they agree and nod. but next day at work, when someone makes a sexist joke or remark, he lets it slide, because social friendliness is an important career tool. and then he becomes part of the problem. you are the part of the problem.

next time, you hear a female worker speaking up on being assaulted by someone who seems such a nice guy and chose to â€œnot see itâ€, just notice. notice how much you lack in courage. that is that courage times 1000, that the assaulted woman had to find to speak up. because, from now on, she will for life be marked as a whore and an attention-seeker. or something even worse, a feminist. 
kavanaugh probably being voted into supreme court on the anniversary of #metoo is symbolical, it is a spit in the face of all of us, assaulted women of the world who dare to speak up. we needed dr. fords victory. it would have been a perfect showcase: a 17 years old boyâ€™s drunken sexist behavior will affect his life too. sexual assault can affect the perpetrator years and years into his future. and that would be justice. because itâ€™s what it does to assaulted women. 
a year after #metoo and all we are left with is #femalerage. share it.

text:
white privilege is... white privilege is when people ask what they should call my husband - but they don't ask what they should call me...i tell them "you can call him glenn". white privilege looks like people smiling at our biracial children as they walk through the grocery store with me, but accusing them of stealing when they walk through with their dad.

it looks like sitting on the train and not having people shift over, or grab their purse tighter.

or entering an elevator and not having someone exit because you are there.

white privilege is walking to the bathroom in a bar on new year's eve and not having people pet my hair as i walk by.

it is the freedom to walk hand in hand with your partner without getting yelled at that "you should know better". it is never having a family member disown you because you fell in love with your soul mate, whose skin color just happened to be different than yours.

white privilege is the ability to travel with your family without having to worry about whether or not it will be safe for you to be there together.

white privilege is never experiencing the devastation of your child being stopped from entering a bathroom at school because he is black.

white privilege is the luxury of not having an opinion or picking a side because you "don't like conflict". it is the freedom to change the channel because you are "not in the mood to deal with that racial stuff again today". my white privilege is painfully obvious...are you brave enough to acknowledge yours?
nothing will change until you do.... white privilege is this post making you feel defensive, or even worse - making you feel nothing at all... don't claim to be an ally to any cause #metoo #blacklivesmatter
#timesup if you are comfortable watching it happen all around you.

it's time to speak up!
it's time to step up!

why?
because allies are not silent
that's why!

#thatswhyseries
#soulconversations
#whiteprivilege
#makeitawkward
#racism #instagood #instadaily #instagram #allies #vote #nomore #ibelieveher

text:
to the good men
.
like so many women in the us right now, i'm exhausted from the kavanaugh hearing. the same night of the hearing, i met a non-white, very privileged man who calmly detailed his grossly sexist ideology, and explained that he didn't think equality was possible between men and women. he described his recent trip to the ukraine, said "feminism doesn't exist there," and explained why that was so appealing. my rage was bursting at the seams as this man looked me in the eye and told me why he deserved more rights than i did.
.
here's what i did: i listened. i gave him time to speak, and time to feel heard and understood. i treated him with the humanity and kindness that was void when he looked at me, a woman, as a lesser being. and then, i softened. "i would love to challenge your perspective for just a second, if i could..." i said. i spoke slowly, softly, and with confidence. he leaned in to listen. i made him feel safe, and he paid attention.
.
i doubt i changed his mind on his search for his mail order bride, but i planted the seed and i'm sure that he will remember my face and our conversation for a very long time.
.
i decided to start spending time with the good men in my life to get that bad taste out of my mouth. i reached out to my guy friends. we had coffees and phone calls and good conversations. sometimes about the hearing, sometimes about nothing in particular. i needed to be reminded that the good men are out there, and i needed to feel safe again.
.
good men: we need you right now. we are tired, exhausted, and hurting. we need you to lean in and listen, and then we need your voices. tell us you're proud of us. tell us you see our fight and our exhaustion. pat us on the back and give us big brother hugs. show us your support and that there are enough of you so that we can feel safe, if only for a moment. that we can breathe long enough to continue fighting. use your voices to stand up for us.
.

.
the ig yoga community has been such an amazing source of support and healing for me over the last 2 years as iâ€™ve shared pieces of my story of trauma and healing. âš¡ï¸âš¡ï¸âš¡ï¸
.
a little over a year ago when #metoo started trending and becoming a part of major headlines i was dealing with my own personal trauma of experiencing the man who raped me being released from prison. september of 2017 was a challenging month. but with my ig yogis by my side i was able to feel a little better. from sharing my story, to hearing other stories, to my #flylikeayogi challenge where we raised almost $15,000 for @rainn, to last week when we all poured out our hearts with #whyididntreport it has been an incredible heartbreaking but hope-bringing year. we will continue to fight - no matter what strikes us down âš¡ï¸. we will continue to hoist each other up. we will continue to spread love and light and not stop till the world is a better place for women and men and children everywhere. we are survivors. we have been struck. but we will not be defeated. âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨
.
â€œtrauma creates change you donâ€™t choose. healing is about creating change you do chooseâ€. - michelle rosenthal âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨
.
so letâ€™s all heal together. âš¡ï¸âš¡ï¸âš¡ï¸
.

#rp the physician denis mukwege, awarded this yearâ€™s nobel peace prize, has spent large parts of his adult life helping the victims of sexual violence in the democratic republic of congo. dr. mukwege and his staff have treated thousands of patients who have fallen victim to such assaults. most of the abuses have been committed in the context of a long-lasting civil war that has cost the lives of more than six million congolese.
mukwege is the foremost, most unifying symbol, both nationally and internationally, of the struggle to end sexual violence in war and armed conflicts. his basic principle is that â€œjustice is everyoneâ€™s businessâ€.
he has repeatedly condemned impunity for mass rape and criticised the congolese government and other countries for not doing enough to stop the use of sexual violence against women as a strategy and weapon of war.

text:
i try to not get involved in politics on social media. most of the time it is pointless and uneducated arguing between closed-minded people. 
this topic, however, hits very close to home. 
i studied a great deal of law in college as i have my ba in political science. i am not an expert, i do not claim to be, but i do believe i have a greater grasp on it than people bickering on facebook. 
that being said, do i think defendants deserve a fair and speedy trial? yes. there is a great deal if merit in "innocent until proven guilty".
an ideal that should be protected and upheld for all people.

however, women (or rather any human being) coming forward should be given the same. and when it comes to sexual violence? they're not. and that, my friends, is the problem. society crucifies survivors and then asks "why they didn't speak up sooner???" speak up sooner to be called a liar? a slut? "what were you wearing?" ... which is entirely contradictory to innocent until proven... our culture is hell bent on keeping the status quo. but it is toxic. it is warped. 
law and order are important but should equally apply to all people. as it is intended. not just white, wealthy, men... the treatment of survivors is wholly unjust.

change is inevitable. 
but don't make the mistake of simply trolling online. write to your senators, rally, speak out, know your rights, defend them! vote. pay attenetion and be vigilant. now is not the time for complacency. the status quo may be skewed but imagine if all of us took action to balance those scales? 
#metoo

text: speaking as a victim of rape myself, my heart is shattered today. following this trial sent me back to that night playing back over and over in my head. and the decision today took me back to the day i tried to report it to the hillsborough county police department and the officer instead lectured me on what i had done wrong to end up in that situation and urged me not to press charges as i didnâ€™t have anything that would hold up in court. i was 19 and didnâ€™t know better. the people that are suppose to represent me and all other victims of sexual violence turned their backs on us. with the senate vote to confirm brett kavanugh into the supreme court, validation is being granted to people like my attacker to continue to not just live their lives, but thrive, without any remorse for the pain, horror, and devastation they put us through. #metoo #timesup #ibelieveher #brettkavanaugh #trumpisnotmypresident #impeachtrump #impeachkavanaugh #fuckthis

text:
when you hear the word "rape", what comes to mind?
.
i know, for me, it usually tended to be something of violent nature. a stranger appearing out of nowhere or a stalker.
.
but that's not always the case. and it wasn't in mine. and i wished i would have known there were more dimensions to it then what the movies show you or what you hear on the news. because i was so confused when it did happen to me.
.
i was with my boyfriend. someone i trusted. i was 19. my first boyfriend, my first kiss, my first time trusting anyone. and he took advantage of that trust. i said no, a lot, all day in fact when he kept asking me about sex. but he still did it anyways, & used my trust to his advantage. i cried because i knew something wasn't right, i had said no, wasn't that was i was supposed to do? but.. it was my boyfriend. is that rape?
.
it felt so wrong & after it was over i wanted to leave immediately & go curl up in a ball forever. then he told me to "just pretend it never happened." and that confirmed it even more. but i was still confused. could i even file a police report on my boyfriend?
.
because of that confusion & fear of what this football player could do to me if i told.. i pretended it never happened. for a year. then when i had a mental breakdown a year to the date & told someone about it, they told me no, that was rape, you said no. it hit me as if it just happened the day before. i knew in my heart it was, but i was never told it could be anything but violent.
.
so to any woman or girl out there wondering if what happened with someone they trusted is rape, if you said no, it is. something i wish i would have known a long time ago before it happened, after it happened, & didn't take 2 therapists to convince me of that. .
i hope my story can help someone today to realize it wasn't your fault. just because it's someone you trust & love doesn't make it ok. and if you're staying because you are confused like i was, please leave, it will not get better. take back your control and your life! .
if you need someone to talk to, please come to me so i can help! we can make it through this together! we are warriors! ğŸ’ªğŸ’—

ğŸ–Š

text: what message are you sending your child when they hear you say, "my child would never allow someone to sexually abuse them" or "my child knows better than to let someone say or do "xyz" to them"? no child wants to be sexually abused, but as we have said many times before, a child is no match for the cunning manipulations of a sexual predator. so if they become victim to abuse and this is the messaging they've heard from you, they will find it very difficult to disclose the abuse to you because they fear what your response will be based on what you've said in the past. not to mention, the predator has also instilled shame, fear, blame, and guilt in them to keep them silent and compliant, which only adds to the reasonings that play out in their minds about why they can't tell you. be careful with your words around your children and be careful what you say to other adults about your children. not only is your child taking it all in, but you just might be talking to your child's abuser who will twist your words and use them against your child! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

untitled (your body is a battleground), 1989, exemplifies barbara krugerâ€™s interest in addressing and interpreting heated political issues of the moment. using a silkscreened frontal photograph of a modelâ€™s face, the artist gives the image additional meaning by dividing the large canvas it occupies into sections; from left to right, the bisected image reverses from positive to negative, and from top to bottom, the face is divided by the emblazoned slogan â€œyour body is a battleground.â€ kruger critiques the objectified standard of symmetry that is applied to feminine beauty and perpetuated by media and advertising. the composition originally included more text and was designed as a poster for the massive pro-choice rally that took place on april 9, 1989, in washington, d.c.
#metoo #enoughisenough #persist #togetherwewill #standtogether #itsonus @barbarakruger #culturechange #itsourtime #whenyouconnectwithart

text:
trigger warning: yes #metoo
(full video in bio link)

when i was 15 years old, i adored and trusted a very charismatic high school biology teacher.  he was so well-loved and popular that students even made a youtube video of him.  i just watched it again after many years.  i noticed that i still cringe at the sight of him.  he was probably 35 years my senior.  yes, deep scars have been left on my mind and body since this was my first sexual encounter. 
i think about what went wrong...how did it happenâ€¦thereâ€™s no blame...just stating what is a fact that...as a child of immigrant parents, my parents worked all the time.  i didnâ€™t have a father figure.  i was craving attention, affection and friendship from older people, older men. throughout my academic career, i have made friends with many teachers.  i always saw myself as more mature and prided myself in my ability to connect with different people. 
one teacher in particular took advantage of this connectionâ€¦

during breaks in our stressful high school schedule, i would always find respite in his quiet classroom.  he also had this calm aura that i was drawn to.  i wanted to get to know him.  so for 3 years, we would hang out in the classroom, puzzle over the puzzles in the sf chronicle, share snacks, and other students would join in and out of our conversations.  i would march to him to complain about a hard test.  i would do my homework there and ask him for help.  my friends thought i was a hermit since i was there all the time.  if they wanted to hang out with me, they would have to come to this classroom.  i enjoyed these innocent times.  i thought i was cultivating a platonic friendship, but he was cultivating something much more than that. 
shit hit the fan right after high school graduation when i was 18 years old.  i was thriving off of his compliments, gifts, deep conversations about life, etc.  the handwritten letters and emails flowed back and forth well into my 2nd year of college at ucsd.  when i went home for a visit, it would always include a visit with him.  he was married but fed me a lie that he and his wife have this understanding to lead... *story continues in comments

â£

â£
and it is no oneâ€™s business why a survivor didnâ€™t report. for myself, it was a gut wrenching and prayer filled decision. the decision to not go public with the worst trauma of my life does not mean iâ€™m lying about it: it means i have chosen not to suffer further abuse by the courts and the justice system.â£
â£
never stop fighting. never stop screaming. ğŸ’™

finally finished #howtobefamous hmm....liked it but didn't love it as much as #howtobuildagirl i will always adore and love everything @mscaitlinmoran writes. much appreciation in slipping in a #metoo moment. if only women back in 1995 were as brave as johanna were and spoke up about their ordeal, then perhaps, today's society of women would have been more protected and ready to say: 'don't even mister, im not at all comfortable with this' 
i'm glad #caitlinmoran highlighted this in her second novel, as johanna deals with it, well, in a johanna kind of way, with a cracking wolverhampton accent. without a doubt, this was much needed back in 95' as it is for our current generation of women, as men such as #jerrysharp shouldn't be allowed to ruin 'bright young girls' he is an utter shameless dick and justice was done, thanks to #johannamorrigan what a legend, what a woman. she sure gets her point across, supporting women. #womenstandingtogether

text:
after living through another day of not being heard then being sold out by yet another politician my sadness and depression has turned to channeled anger and a deep commitment to seeing this through so young girls do not think this is the norm
.
.
my friend jen studies mountain lions and had posted this picture. it symbolized everything i felt internally and i asked her if she could send it to me
.
.
this is what she said about her lion: oh yeah, i love the female cougars, they are so badass and beautiful, they are totally my role models for feminine power.  the cool thing is these gals regularly take down the biggest bull elk (more so than the males) and are much more prolific killers (it takes a lot to raise kittens into adulthood). i have pics of them in my office and on my desktop to remind me of what i strive to be, especially in times like these. ğŸ’•
.
.

text:
as i was coloring wonder woman brown yesterday, i began to feel like i was doing something out of the ordinary and going against the grain. and then i began to ask myself... why do i have this feeling that celebrating my skin tone and wanting the portrait to look like me is rebellious? how is it that iâ€™m subconsciously under the pressures of feeling like i must adjust to the white american standard as though i wasnâ€™t birthed here as were many of my ancestors. so because i am american, shouldnâ€™t my black skin be enough? 
i had so many white baby dolls and i donâ€™t remember a time in elementary school that i ever colored my portraits as a mirror image of myself with dark brown skin.
.
.
i like to believe that i am very self-aware but thereâ€™s always something that happens that invites my mind to a new level of consciousness about who i am, what i believe and how i work hard to live above the influence but can still be affected by things that have been instilled in me subliminally being that i am a black woman living in america. .
.
it is my mission that little black girls begin to understand their value and see themselves as super heroes and warriors because it may not be on television or in the cartoons but itâ€™s in our dna! .
. 
oppression has been embedded in my psychi and i will continue to be intentional about acknowledging my behaviors that prove this so that i can fight against it. .
. 
black women, you are enough! being a black woman is to be celebrated. we are to overcome the narrative that we are to be undervalued and mistreated despite what messages the media, music and movies convey about our worth. i love all women but i just have a special place in my heart for black queens! ğŸ‘‘

i am the people â€” the mob â€” the crowd â€” the mass.
do you know that all the great work of the world is done through me?

i am the audience that witnesses history. the 
napoleons come from me and the lincolns.

for much plowing. terrible storms pass

and wasted. i forget. everything but death 
comes to me and makes me work and give up 
what i have. and i forget.
sometimes i growl, shake myself and spatter a 
few red drops for history to remember. then â€”
i forget.
when i, the people, learn to remember, when i,

no longer forget who robbed me last year, who
played me for a fool â€” then there will be no
speaker in all the world say the name: â€œthe
people,â€ with any fleck of a sneer in his voice
or any far-off smile of derision.
the mob â€” the crowd â€” the mass â€” will arrive then.
.

.

text: women are goddesses! we are able to carry a human being inside of us...creating life...then giving birth...making food for that life. it hurts my heart that women, as a whole, are not revered, but instead looked down upon as a weaker species. soon enough these machismo, moronic men in "power" will be dead. i am raising the next generation. my boys know the worth of a woman, as well as themselves! they know what is important in our world. they know how to respect people around them and how they should be respected in turn. i don't know what else to say...i am sad. i have been raped (more than once) and sexually assaulted by a family member. why say anything when it makes no difference?? i don't post this for an argument, or for sympathy, just for people to think about it. think about the choices you make and think about the children you are raising, and the lives around you. #vote #metoo #godessesriseup #raisinggoodpeople #letsburnittotheground #fuckitall #boymom #notmypresident

huge congratulations to 2018 #nobelpeaceprize laureate, nadia murad, who has been a brave and powerful voice for survivors of human trafficking and victims of sexual violence. in 2014, at the age of 19, murad was kidnapped in iraq, held hostage, and constantly subjected to sexual violence. after escaping 3 months of captivity, she started seeking justice for victims everywhere, telling her story to the world time and again, even though that meant reliving horrific memories of abuse and suffering. thank you nadia, for your courage to speak up and seek justice, not just for yourself, but for all survivors of sexual violence.
.

text:
as you prepare to join us for the festival this year, we ask that you endorse this very important code of conduct clause to ensure a safe, pleasant and fun experience for everyone attending or involved.

@photoktm is committed to creating a safe and respectful environment for all participants as well as the local community, who host us so graciously.

the festival will not tolerate any/all harassment and intimidation of a sexual, physical, verbal, emotional or any other nature based on gender, sexual orientation, age, appearance, marital status, religion, ability or any other excuse at any time of day or night, at any festival gathering including parties. substances consumed can not be taken as an excuse.

should the festival be notified of any bullshit, prior to attending, during and after attending the festival, the festival reserves the right to terminate any/all association with you.

should you be a witness to any bullshit during the festival, we ask that you not be a silent embarrassed by-stander but offer your support to the person needing it in the way they deem safest.

this clause is not meant to offend anyone who does not plan to offend others. and it shall not get in the way of us all having a perfectly wonderful time together.

we look forward to seeing you in kathmandu!

please read + sign on our registration page:
http://www.photoktm.com/register/ link also in bio ğŸ‘†ğŸ¼

text:
#doit #spicegirls #currentmood #metoo #yotecreo #girlpower #women #womenempowerment 
it's just another thing keep your eye fixed on the road
do what your mama said
i will not be told
keep your mouth shut, keep your legs shut
go back in your place
blameless, shameless, damsel in disgrace
who cares what they say
because the rules are for breaking
(i'll said ya)
who made them anyway
you gotta show what you feel
don't hide
come on and do it
don't care how you look, it's just how you feel
come on and do it
you gotta make it real
come on and do it
it's time to free what's in your soul
you gotta get it right, this time
come on freak out lose control
remember things like this should be seen and never heard
give a little respect to me & it will be returned
keep your head down, keep your nose clean
go back against the wall
girl there's no way out for you
you are sure to fall
who cares what they do
because it's yours for the taking
so it's not for you anyway
make your own rules to live by
come on and do it
don't care how you look, it's just how you feel
come on and do it
you gotta make it real
come on and do it
it's time to free what's in your soul
you gotta get it right, this time
come on freak out lose control
you might do the wrong thing (might do the wrong thing)
for the right reasons (for the right reason)
don't just do the right thing (don't do the right thing)
to be pleasing (to be pleasin baby)

text:
been listening to coltrane since yesterday when 
kavanaugh was confirmed
and my head was slammed against a wall called amerikka.  i need time to blow off steam so hot and deep it flips a finger at antebellum slavery cause this right here is chains and ass whippings you canâ€™t see coming, canâ€™t see the welts but that only makes them throb worse, raise redder-uglier.  itâ€™s been centuries, this shit.  itâ€™s psychological waterboarding.  it hurts every which way. i wanna throw up the hope obama gave me and steal myself away, take a dump in the rose garden and fertilize the hate since thatâ€™s all there is. i listen to a love supreme and pray that like john, i can kick the drug habit, crush the needle that fed me american slang: equality, hope, post-racial, yes we can.  iâ€™d rather love only jazz while i sweat and puke and shiver for a week and then slowly, carefully recover whateverâ€™s left of my political ideals.  music is my affirmative action. my muse is john, back in the day, holed up in a room with bread and water until the heroin stopped the torture. iâ€™m there. done believing in a system so rusted over it has turned clocks back to cotton fields and railroad songs. iâ€™m swinging arcs and banging names of ancestors who bled for nothing.  nothing. thatâ€™s how i feel a day after kavanaugh was confirmed and iâ€™m going through withdrawal so i donâ€™t overdose on delusion.

â€œbefore this weekend jettisons our higher cognitive functions into the atmosphere of apathy. let me remind you that youâ€™re amazing. no really: you are actually, without exaggeration, amazing. at no time in human history have we been this evolved as a species (cue man farting the star spangled banner). weâ€™ve never distributed our intelligence, productivity, or quality of life to so many people. weâ€™ve gone into the depths of our oceans as well as our minds, and into space, and looked under our skin, and survived to be more. and we did it because we are all hungry. itâ€™s easy to eat anything when youâ€™re starving, or when youâ€™ve never tasted the freshness of fruit from our own #garden... itâ€™s our #power, which lies not in our ability to make or build or create, but in the #energy we transform or transfer throughout our lives. while my instinct is often to react to our ignorance or judgment or actions with a hammer, i know that hammer is to only be used to stop another hammer. so this weekend, and maybe next weekend, and the next, so much so that it flows over into your week and infests all your days... i hope that you show us how amazing we are by using the heart instead of the hammer. or perhaps the brush, or pen, or your voice. itâ€™s just energy. going from one thing to another and so on. from years ago to yesterday in front of a lens to a phone made unfairly to your eyes and your mind and hopefully, your heart.â€â€”@alex.fiore

text:
you can recognize survivors of abuse by their courage. when silence is so very inviting, they step forward and share their truth so others know they aren't alone. #metoo i was a victim of adam croasdell and will not be silenced, threatened or shamed as a survivor for his actions anymore by him or whomever he has help him whether fans or friends he enlists. in november our joint interviews will be airing stateside. we will be sharing our experiences as a survivor of his abuse, pictures to videos in conjunction and the various methods he used to try and silence us. iâ€™m one of five women who have spoken up and been interviewed if adam croasdell has physically or mentally abused you or harassed your under multiple instagrams whether alone or with fans or his friends please come forward with hashtag #adamcroasdellabusedmetoo we would like to have you interviewed and speak out  against him to stop him from silencing another woman if youâ€™re scared and have any chat logs, texts, videos, audios or pictures we will take those to if you prefer to not be named but still want to help. your safety is more important and adam has a history of bullying and harassing women whether by internet or outside of it it does not matter if it happened on or offline. there are also six photographers who are going to interview and sue him for violating their copyrights, harassment and vandalism of their work which he did under multiple instagrams if heâ€™s done that to you to please let us know we will give you the information for that process use #adamcroasdellvandalized thank you for your help and supporting and stopping adam from vandalizing photographers work and other women from being hurt by this animal. if we stay silent we empower abusers creating more women to be victims. we need to support survivors instead of shaming or blaming them because a celebrity or person in power commits these atrocities.

text:
warrioresses who've carried the flag for lifetimes. that's who we are. 
know this: 
power doesn't always look pretty. it's far from perfect. it's not a straight road. we don't always feel her, but power, she never leaves us. she is the bearer of our souls. she is the fire in our belly. she is the light on our path. she is the strength in our way. she is every feeling in our bodies. every. single. one.
